				<h2 class="title icon icon0">
					Re: Judge: Facebook Page Is Protected by Free Speech
				</h2>
				

						
						
				<div class="content">
					<div id="post_message_1583863">
						<blockquote class="postcontent restore ">
							<div class="bbcode_container">
	<div class="bbcode_quote">
		<div class="quote_container">
			<div class="bbcode_quote_container"></div>
			
				<div class="bbcode_postedby">
					<img src="images/misc/quote_icon.png" alt="Quote" /> Originally Posted by <strong>ChildovGhad</strong>
					<a href="showthread.php?p=1583806#post1583806" rel="nofollow"><img class="inlineimg" src="images/buttons/viewpost-right.png" alt="View Post" /></a>
				</div>
				<div class="message">Call me a nigger, Ill kick your ass then go fight for your right to call me a nigger.</div>
			
		</div>
	</div>
</div>The thing is, that's sort of what the teacher did. For 'I'll kick your ass' read 'I'll suspend you'.<br />
<br />
Haven't we always argued on this board that free speech doesn't mean you are free from social consequences for your speech, just that the government can't lock you up over it. This was a social consequence - and a very mild one at that. Now she can sue over it?<br />
 <br />
<div class="bbcode_container">
	<div class="bbcode_quote">
		<div class="quote_container">
			<div class="bbcode_quote_container"></div>
			
				At the Business Insider, Erin Geiger Smith said it was &quot;difficult to see how, aside from technology, it's any different than a student who writes a note at home (which is where Evans created the site) whining about a disagreement with their teacher.&quot; Smith says it's a clear case of the First Amendment at work. &quot;If she had done it at school and it was disruptive, that would be different,&quot; Smith wrote. &quot;But if it's an outside-of-school activity that remains opinion-based (i.e., isn't slanderous), then this is just a byproduct of technology and the First Amendment.&quot;
			
		</div>
	</div>
</div>I agree. She has the absolute right to say something like this on Facebook. And the teacher has an absolute right to suspend her over it if she wants to.
						</blockquote>
					</div>

					
				</div>
			</div>
			
			<div class="after_content">
				
                                       
                                 
				
