				<h2 class="title icon icon0">
					Re: Judge: Facebook Page Is Protected by Free Speech
				</h2>
				

						
						
				<div class="content">
					<div id="post_message_1583865">
						<blockquote class="postcontent restore ">
							So your teacher should be able to suspend you for things you do when you're not at school or doing school-related activities?<br />
<br />
Should she be able to suspend you for not cleaning your room?  For refusing to eat your peas?  Because your mom cut in front of her at the Walmart parking lot?<br />
<br />
Actions done publicly should have an expectation of public response.  But not the use of the State's coercive power to carry out that response.  The teacher could have gone to the girl's house off-hours and chewed her out (or better sat down with her to talk about the situation).  That'd be the proper response.  Using her State-derived power to punish the student for doing something on the student's own time is not the answer.<br />
<br />
Assumption here is that this is a public school and as such is an extension of Government.  Put that in your pipe and slippery slopery smoke it.
						</blockquote>
					</div>

					
				</div>
			</div>
			
