			<div class="postrow has_after_content">
				
				
				<h2 class="title icon icon0">
					Re: Judge: Facebook Page Is Protected by Free Speech
				</h2>
				

						
						
				<div class="content">
					<div id="post_message_1583867">
						<blockquote class="postcontent restore ">
							<div class="bbcode_container">
	<div class="bbcode_quote">
		<div class="quote_container">
			<div class="bbcode_quote_container"></div>
			
				<div class="bbcode_postedby">
					<img src="images/misc/quote_icon.png" alt="Quote" /> Originally Posted by <strong>Grindel</strong>
					<a href="showthread.php?p=1583865#post1583865" rel="nofollow"><img class="inlineimg" src="images/buttons/viewpost-right.png" alt="View Post" /></a>
				</div>
				<div class="message">So your teacher should be able to suspend you for things you do when you're not at school or doing school-related activities?<br />
<br />
Should she be able to suspend you for not cleaning your room?  For refusing to eat your peas?  Because your mom cut in front of her at the Walmart parking lot?<br />
<br />
Actions done publicly should have an expectation of public response.  But not the use of the State's coercive power to carry out that response.  The teacher could have gone to the girl's house off-hours and chewed her out (or better sat down with her to talk about the situation).  That'd be the proper response.  Using her State-derived power to punish the student for doing something on the student's own time is not the answer.<br />
<br />
Assumption here is that this is a public school and as such is an extension of Government.  Put that in your pipe and slippery slopery smoke it.</div>
			
		</div>
	</div>
</div>It's irrelevant if it's a public school. All schools have the power to suspend, public or private.<br />
<br />
Let's say that she starts working for the government itself. Let's say she starts a facebook page where she has 'My boss is the worst boss I've ever had', and let's say the boss finds out about it like her teacher did. Are we really saying her boss can't suspend her because he works for the government? <br />
<br />
Could the teacher have handled it differently? Of course. Can the teacher be criticised for her actions? Of course. That is the social consequence thing at work again. Should the teacher get <i>sued</i> for choosing to suspend her for it? No.
						</blockquote>
					</div>

					
				</div>
			</div>
			
